Magnitude of the fluctuation in the exchange rates between the US and Russia is bounded by a current bond payment (April 29th, $564.8M and $ 84.4M on a 2022 Eurobond and 2042 bond). These payments, made in US dollars, avoided the risk of a sovereign credit default on May 4. It has currently signaled that it would make payments, in US dollars, on a remaining $2 billion bond payment due on May 27. Default on this payment (ie., non payment or payment in non US currency) will result in its first sovereign default since the Bolsheviks took power in 1917. The likelihood or probability of avoiding a default (used interchangeably, P) or a default (1-P) effects how much the devaluation in the ruble relative to the dollar will occur. If the event (1-P) occurs, it is highly likely that we will see a significant weakening of the ruble against the dollar. Given the current baseline conditioned on P we can expect the current trend in the exchange rate pair to continue, else (1-P) results in a significant fluctuation in the difference between the currency pair. Risk averse decision-makers act rationally when EU(P) > 0 and risk acceptant decision-makers act irrationally when EU(1 - P) < 0.

Very soon after the February 24 invasion the Russian government required that Russian companies convert 80% of revenues from foreign sales to rubles. See https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2022/03/31/ruble-recovery-sanctions-russia/. Primarily energy sales, but also minerals and fertilizer, continue to generate enough hard currency to finance the war. This has apparently been enough to stabilize the ruble. According to leaked FSB accounts, Russia has funding for the war in Ukraine only through June. There are two scenarios: either (1) there is a negotiated agreement in place by that point or (2) the war is ongoing. In either case, it seems unlikely that sanctions would be removed until Russia could verify it was upholding an agreement. Even if sanctions were removed prior to June, it would take time for the rouble to recover. Given Russia's unpredictability, companies will likely be less interested in going back into this market, which will subdue any recovery. The rouble is already at 155 to $1 USD; I struggle to see a way for any recovery with sanctions still in place and am doubtful that negotiations would lead to a quick enough resolution for currency to rebound by July.
